item.label: Dura
item.name: Dura
item.description: The dura mater is the outermost and thickest collagenous layer of the three layers of meninges. Within the skull its 'outer' layer adheres tightly to the inside of the skull, constituting the periosteum. An 'inner' meningeal layer separates out as reflections between parts of the cerebral hemisphere, i.e. cerebral falx or between the cerebral hemispheres and posterior fossa, i.e. tentorium cerebelli. In the spinal dura mater there is a single layer separated from the vertebral periosteum by the epidural space.

item.label: Dural reflections
item.name: Dural reflections
item.description: The internal meningeal layer of the dura forms folds of dura known as the dural reflections.  They extend between portions of the brain, such as the cerebral falx that extends between the cerebral hemispheres.  These infoldings or reflections divide the cranial cavity into compartments, forming partial partitions between parts of the brain.  They also provide structural support.  Included are the cerebral falx, cerebellar tentorium, cerebellar falx and sellar diaphragm.

item.label: Tentorium cerebelli
item.name: Tentorium cerebelli
item.description: The tentorium cerebelli is the dural reflection located superior to the cerebellum and beneath the temporal and occipital lobes of the cerebral hemispheres. The midbrain portion of the brainstem passes through a midline opening in the tentorium, the tentorial notch; this opening also allows communication between the middle cranial fossa (supratentorial) and posterior cranial fossa (infratentorial).

item.label: Diaphragma sellae
item.name: Diaphragma sellae
item.description: The diaphragma sella is that portion of dura mater that covers the pituitary fossa (sella turcica), leaving a small opening for passage of the infundibulum or pituitary stalk.

item.label: Cranial fossae
item.name: Cranial fossae
item.description: The internal aspect of the base of the skull is subdivided into three compartments or fossae:  anterior, middle and posterior cranial fossae.

item.label: Anterior cranial fossa
item.name: Anterior cranial fossa
item.description: The anterior cranial fossa refers to that portion of the interior of the base of the skull that is formed mainly by the frontal bone.  A significant feature of this fossa is the cribriform plate, through which the olfactory nerves pass to enter the cranial cavity.  The frontal lobes of the brain occupy the anterior cranial fossa.

item.label: Middle cranial fossa
item.name: Middle cranial fossa
item.description: The middle cranial fossa refers to that portion of the interior of the base of the skull occupied by the temporal lobes as well as important midline structures.  It is located posterior and inferior to the anterior cranial fossa and is marked off from the posterior fossa by the dorsum sellae.

item.label: Posterior cranial fossa
item.name: Posterior cranial fossa
item.description: The posterior cranial fossa is the largest and deepest of the three cranial fossae.  The cerebellum, pons and medulla are contained within the posterior fossa.  The tentorium cerebelli forms the roof of the fossa so that communication between the middle and posterior fossae is through the incisure or notch of the tentorium.  The midbrain lies within the tentorial notch.
